<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-812-100  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 812 100.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The Seybold Report on Publishing Systems  Oct 9 1989 v19 n3 p37(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Seybold Publications Inc. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>InterMedia wins case on user interface: Aladdin told not to copydisplay. (InterMedia Graphics Systems wins suit vs. AladdinSoftware)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   InterMedia Graphic Systems (cases)Aladdin Software (cases).andO;Topic:     Law SuitGraphical User InterfaceNorwayGraphics Software.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>InterMedia wins case on user interface For the first time in European legalhistory, we believe, a judgment has been given regarding the morality ofcopying a user interface.andP;  Following a long battle in the Norwegian courts,InterMedia Graphic Systems won its case against Aladdin Software S/A.andO;InterMedia claimed that Aladdin Software had imitated its user interface, andby doing so had caused confusion in the market, thereby taking advantage ofInterMedia's goodwill to make sales and to establish itself in themarketplace in Scandinavia.andM;The judgment of the court stated, &quot;The Court must therefore take as its pointof departure common business morals in considering whether there has been abreach of sound business practices.&quot;andP;  The court added that the defendant(Aladdin Software) had a duty to avoid imitation of elements that are not ofa purely functional character .andP;  .  .  and a duty to create visualdifferences in the screen displays, wherever this could reasonably beachieved, to avoid the risk of confusion or a situation in which thedefendant in some way sponged on the plaintiff's marketing.andP;  InterMedia wasawarded damages and costs.andO;</TEXT></DOC>